# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: genomics-computing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The **Burrows–Wheeler transform** (**BWT**) rearranges a character string into runs of similar characters, in a manner that can be reversed to recover the original string.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] Since compression techniques such as move-to-front transform and run-length encoding are more effective when such runs are present, the BWT can be used as a preparatory step to improve the efficiency of a compression algorithm, and is used this way in software such as bzip2.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The algorithm can be implemented efficiently using a suffix array thus reaching linear time complexity.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] It was invented by David Wheeler in 1983, and later published by him and Michael Burrows in 1994.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] Their paper included a compression algorithm, called the **Block-sorting Lossless Data Compression Algorithm** or **BSLDCA**, that compresses data by using the BWT followed by move-to-front coding and Huffman coding or arithmetic coding.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The transform is done by constructing a matrix (known as the Burrows–Wheeler matrix) whose rows are the circular shifts of the input text, sorted in lexicographic order, then taking the final column of that matrix.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The output of the encoding phase is the last column `L = BNN^AA$A` after step 3, and the index (0-based) `I` of the row containing the original string `S`, in this case `I = 6`.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] It is not necessary to use both `$` and `^`, but at least one must be used, else we cannot invert the transform, since all circular permutations of a string have the same Burrows–Wheeler transform.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The following pseudocode gives a simple (though inefficient) way to calculate the BWT and its inverse.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] It assumes that the input string `s` contains a special character "EOF", which is the last character and occurs nowhere else in the text.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] If the original string had several substrings that occurred often, then the BWT-transformed string will have several places where a single character is repeated many times in a row, creating more-easily-compressible data.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] Similarly, rotations beginning with "e " are grouped together, but "e " is often preceded by "h", so we see the output above contains a run of five consecutive "h" characters.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] Thus it can be seen that the success of this transform depends upon one value having a high probability of occurring before a sequence, so that in general it needs fairly long samples (a few kilobytes at least) of appropriate data (such as text).
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The remarkable thing about the BWT is not that it generates a more easily encoded output—an ordinary sort would do that—but that it does this *reversibly*, allowing the original document to be re-generated from the last column data.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] Take the final table in the BWT algorithm, and erase all but the last column.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] Given only this information, you can easily reconstruct the first column.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The last column tells you all the characters in the text, so just sort these characters alphabetically to get the first column.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] Then, the last and first columns (of each row) together give you all *pairs* of successive characters in the document, where pairs are taken cyclically so that the last and first character form a pair.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] Sorting the list of pairs gives the first *and second* columns.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] To obtain the third column, the last column is again prepended to the table, and the rows are sorted lexicographically.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] Continuing in this manner, you can reconstruct the entire list.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] Then, the row with the "end of file" character at the end is the original text.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] A number of optimizations can make these algorithms run more efficiently without changing the output.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] There is no need to represent the table in either the encoder or decoder.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] In the encoder, each row of the table can be represented by a single pointer into the strings, and the sort performed using the indices.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] In the decoder, there is also no need to store the table, and the decoded string can be generated one character at a time from left to right.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] Comparative sorting can even be avoided in favor of linear sorting, with performance proportional to the alphabet size and string length.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] A "character" in the algorithm can be a byte, or a bit, or any other convenient size.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] One may also make the observation that mathematically, the encoded string can be computed as a simple modification of the suffix array, and suffix arrays can be computed with linear time and memory.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] There is no need to have an actual 'EOF' character.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] Instead, a pointer can be used that remembers where in a string the 'EOF' would be if it existed.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] In this approach, the output of the BWT must include both the transformed string, and the final value of the pointer.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The inverse transform then shrinks it back down to the original size: it is given a string and a pointer, and returns just a string.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] A complete description of the algorithms can be found in Burrows and Wheeler's paper, or in a number of online sources.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The algorithms vary somewhat by whether EOF is used, and in which direction the sorting was done.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] In fact, the original formulation did not use an EOF marker.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] Since any rotation of the input string will lead to the same transformed string, the BWT cannot be inverted without adding an EOF marker to the end of the input or doing something equivalent, making it possible to distinguish the input string from all its rotations.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] Increasing the size of the alphabet (by appending the EOF character) makes later compression steps awkward.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] There is a bijective version of the transform, by which the transformed string uniquely identifies the original, and the two have the same length and contain exactly the same characters, just in a different order.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The bijective transform is computed by factoring the input into a non-increasing sequence of Lyndon words; such a factorization exists and is unique by the Chen–Fox–Lyndon theorem, and may be found in linear time and constant space.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The algorithm sorts the rotations of all the words; as in the Burrows–Wheeler transform, this produces a sorted sequence of *n* strings.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The transformed string is then obtained by picking the final character of each string in this sorted list.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The one important caveat here is that strings of different lengths are not ordered in the usual way; the two strings are repeated forever, and the infinite repeats are sorted.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] For example, "ORO" precedes "OR" because "OROORO..." precedes "OROROR...".
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] For example, the text "^BANANA$" is transformed into "ANNBAA^$" through these steps (the red $ character indicates the EOF pointer) in the original string.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The EOF character is unneeded in the bijective transform, so it is dropped during the transform and re-added to its proper place in the file.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The string is broken into Lyndon words so the words in the sequence are decreasing using the comparison method above.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] (Note that we're sorting '^' as succeeding other characters.) "^BANANA" becomes (^) (B) (AN) (AN) (A).
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] Up until the last step, the process is identical to the inverse Burrows–Wheeler process, but here it will not necessarily give rotations of a single sequence; it instead gives rotations of Lyndon words (which will start to repeat as the process is continued).
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] Here, we can see (repetitions of) four distinct Lyndon words: (A), (AN) (twice), (B), and (^).
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] (NANA... doesn't represent a distinct word, as it is a cycle of ANAN....) At this point, these words are sorted into reverse order: (^), (B), (AN), (AN), (A).
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The whole string is now a Lyndon word, and running it through the bijective process will therefore result in a transformed result that, when inverted, gives back the Lyndon word, with no need for reassembling at the end.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The bijective transform includes eight runs of identical characters.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] In total, 18 characters are used in these runs.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] When a text is edited, its Burrows–Wheeler transform will change.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] This Python implementation sacrifices speed for simplicity: the program is short, but takes more than the linear time that would be desired in a practical implementation.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] It essentially does what the pseudocode section does.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The inverse transform repeatedly inserts `r` as the left column of the table and sorts the table.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] After the whole table is built, it returns the row that ends with ETX, minus the STX and ETX.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] Following implementation notes from Manzini, it is equivalent to use a simple null character suffix instead.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The sorting should be done in colexicographic order (string read right-to-left), i.e.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] (The above control codes actually fail to satisfy EOF being the last character; the two codes are actually the *first*.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] As a lossless compression algorithm the Burrows–Wheeler transform offers the important quality that its encoding is reversible and hence the original data may be recovered from the resulting compression.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The lossless quality of Burrows algorithm has provided for different algorithms with different purposes in mind.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] To name a few, Burrows–Wheeler transform is used in algorithms for sequence alignment, image compression, data compression, etc.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The following is a compilation of some uses given to the Burrows–Wheeler Transform.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The advent of next-generation sequencing (NGS) techniques at the end of the 2000s decade has led to another application of the Burrows–Wheeler transformation.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] In NGS, DNA is fragmented into small pieces, of which the first few bases are sequenced, yielding several millions of "reads", each 30 to 500 base pairs ("DNA characters") long.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] In many experiments, e.g., in ChIP-Seq, the task is now to align these reads to a reference genome, i.e., to the known, nearly complete sequence of the organism in question (which may be up to several billion base pairs long).
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] A number of alignment programs, specialized for this task, were published, which initially relied on hashing (e.g., Eland, SOAP, or Maq).
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] In an effort to reduce the memory requirement for sequence alignment, several alignment programs were developed (Bowtie, BWA, and SOAP2) that use the Burrows–Wheeler transform.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The Burrows–Wheeler transformation has proved to be fundamental for image compression applications.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] For example, Showed a compression pipeline based on the application of the Burrows–Wheeler transformation followed by inversion, run-length, and arithmetic encoders.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The pipeline developed in this case is known as Burrows–Wheeler transform with an inversion encoder (BWIC).
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The results shown by BWIC are shown to outperform the compression performance of well-known and widely used algorithms like Lossless JPEG and JPEG 2000.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] BWIC is shown to outperform those in terms of final compression size of radiography medical images on the order of 5.1% and 4.1% respectively.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The improvements are achieved by combining BWIC and a pre-BWIC scan of the image in a vertical snake order fashion.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] More recently, additional works have shown the implementation of the Burrows–Wheeler Transform in conjunction with the known move-to-front transform (MTF) achieve near lossless compression of images.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] Cox et al. presented a genomic compression scheme that uses BWT as the algorithm applied during the first stage of compression of several genomic datasets including the human genomic information.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] Their work proposed that BWT compression could be enhanced by including a second stage compression mechanism called same-as-previous encoding ("SAP"), which makes use of the fact that suffixes of two or more prefix letters could be equal.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] With the compression mechanism BWT-SAP, Cox et al. showed that in the genomic database ERA015743, 135.5 GB in size, the compression scheme BWT-SAP compresses the ERA015743 dataset by around 94%, to 8.2 GB.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] BWT has also been proved to be useful on sequence prediction which is a common area of study in machine learning and natural-language processing.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] In particular, Ktistakis et al. proposed a sequence prediction scheme called SuBSeq that exploits the lossless compression of data of the Burrows–Wheeler transform.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] SuBSeq exploits BWT by extracting the FM-index and then performing a series of operations called backwardSearch, forwardSearch, neighbourExpansion, and getConsequents in order to search for predictions given a suffix.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] The predictions are then classified based on a weight and put into an array from which the element with the highest weight is given as the prediction from the SuBSeq algorithm.
[src:genomics-computing/burrows-wheeler-transform] SuBSeq has been shown to outperform state of the art algorithms for sequence prediction both in terms of training time and accuracy.
[src:genomics-computing/de-bruijn-graph] In graph theory, an n-dimensional **De Bruijn graph** of m symbols is a directed graph representing overlaps between sequences of symbols.
[src:genomics-computing/de-bruijn-graph] It has mn vertices, consisting of all possible length-n sequences of the given symbols; the same symbol may appear multiple times in a sequence.
[src:genomics-computing/de-bruijn-graph] If one of the vertices can be expressed as another vertex by shifting all its symbols by one place to the left and adding a new symbol at the end of this vertex, then the latter has a directed edge to the former vertex.
[src:genomics-computing/de-bruijn-graph] Although De Bruijn graphs are named after Nicolaas Govert de Bruijn, they were invented independently by both de Bruijn and I.
[src:genomics-computing/de-bruijn-graph] Much earlier, Camille Flye Sainte-Marie implicitly used their properties.
[src:genomics-computing/de-bruijn-graph] The line graph construction of the three smallest binary De Bruijn graphs is depicted below.
[src:genomics-computing/de-bruijn-graph] As can be seen in the illustration, each vertex of the n-dimensional De Bruijn graph corresponds to an edge of the (*n* − 1)-dimensional De Bruijn graph, and each edge in the n-dimensional De Bruijn graph corresponds to a two-edge path in the (*n* − 1)-dimensional De Bruijn graph.
[src:genomics-computing/de-bruijn-graph] The Bernoulli map (also called the 2*x* mod 1 map for *m* = 2) is an ergodic dynamical system, which can be understood to be a single shift of a m-adic number.
[src:genomics-computing/de-bruijn-graph] The trajectories of this dynamical system correspond to walks in the De Bruijn graph, where the correspondence is given by mapping each real x in the interval [0,1) to the vertex corresponding to the first n digits in the base-m representation of x.
[src:genomics-computing/de-bruijn-graph] Equivalently, walks in the De Bruijn graph correspond to trajectories in a one-sided subshift of finite type.
[src:genomics-computing/de-bruijn-graph] Embeddings resembling this one can be used to show that the binary De Bruijn graphs have queue number 2 and that they have book thickness at most 5.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Knowledge of **DNA sequences** has become indispensable for basic biological research, DNA Genographic Projects and in numerous applied fields such as medical diagnosis, biotechnology, forensic biology, virology and biological systematics.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Comparing healthy and mutated DNA sequences can diagnose different diseases including various cancers, characterize antibody repertoire, and can be used to guide patient treatment.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Having a quick way to sequence DNA allows for faster and more individualized medical care to be administered, and for more organisms to be identified and cataloged.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The rapid advancements in DNA sequencing technology have played a crucial role in sequencing complete genomes of humans, as well as numerous animal, plant, and microbial species.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The first DNA sequences were obtained in the early 1970s by academic researchers using laborious methods based on two-dimensional chromatography.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Following the development of fluorescence-based sequencing methods with a DNA sequencer, DNA sequencing has become easier and orders of magnitude faster.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA sequencing can be used to determine the sequence of individual genes, larger genetic regions (i.e. clusters of genes or operons), full chromosomes, or entire genomes of any organism.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA sequencing is also the most efficient way to indirectly sequence RNA or proteins (via their open reading frames).
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In fact, DNA sequencing has become a key technology in many areas of biology and other sciences such as medicine, forensics, and anthropology.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Sequencing is used in molecular biology to study genomes and the proteins they encode.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Information obtained using sequencing allows researchers to identify changes in genes and noncoding DNA (including regulatory sequences), associations with diseases and phenotypes, and identify potential drug targets.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Since DNA is an informative macromolecule in terms of transmission from one generation to another, DNA sequencing is used in evolutionary biology to study how different organisms are related and how they evolved.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In February 2021, scientists reported, for the first time, the sequencing of DNA from animal remains, a mammoth in this instance, over a million years old, the oldest DNA sequenced to date.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The field of metagenomics involves identification of organisms present in a body of water, sewage, dirt, debris filtered from the air, or swab samples from organisms.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Knowing which organisms are present in a particular environment is critical to research in ecology, epidemiology, microbiology, and other fields.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Sequencing enables researchers to determine which types of microbes may be present in a microbiome, for example.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] As most viruses are too small to be seen by a light microscope, sequencing is one of the main tools in virology to identify and study the virus.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Viral genomes can be based in DNA or RNA.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] RNA viruses are more time-sensitive for genome sequencing, as they degrade faster in clinical samples.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Traditional Sanger sequencing and next-generation sequencing are used to sequence viruses in basic and clinical research, as well as for the diagnosis of emerging viral infections, molecular epidemiology of viral pathogens, and drug-resistance testing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] There are more than 2.3 million unique viral sequences in GenBank.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In 2019, NGS has surpassed traditional Sanger as the most popular approach for generating viral genomes.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] During the 1997 avian influenza outbreak, viral sequencing determined that the influenza sub-type originated through reassortment between quail and poultry.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This led to legislation in Hong Kong that prohibited selling live quail and poultry together at market.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Viral sequencing can also be used to estimate when a viral outbreak began by using a molecular clock technique.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Medical technicians may sequence genes (or, theoretically, full genomes) from patients to determine if there is risk of genetic diseases.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This is a form of genetic testing, though not all genetic tests involve complete genome DNA sequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] As of 2013 DNA sequencing was increasingly used to diagnose and treat rare diseases.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] As more and more genes are identified that cause rare genetic diseases, molecular diagnoses for patients become more mainstream.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA sequencing allows clinicians to identify genetic diseases, improve disease management, provide reproductive counseling, and more effective therapies.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Gene sequencing panels are used to identify multiple potential genetic causes of a suspected disorder.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Also, DNA sequencing may be useful for determining a specific bacteria, to allow for more precise antibiotics treatments, hereby reducing the risk of creating antimicrobial resistance in bacteria populations.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA sequencing may be used along with DNA profiling methods for forensic identification and paternity testing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA testing has evolved tremendously in the last few decades to ultimately link a DNA print to what is under investigation.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The DNA patterns in fingerprint, saliva, hair follicles, etc. uniquely separate each living organism from another.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Testing DNA is a technique which can detect specific genomes in a DNA strand to produce a unique and individualized pattern.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The canonical structure of DNA has four bases: thymine (T), adenine (A), cytosine (C), and guanine (G).
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA sequencing is the determination of the physical order of these bases in a molecule of DNA.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] However, there are many other bases that may be present in a molecule.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In some viruses (specifically, bacteriophage), cytosine may be replaced by hydroxymethyl- or hydroxymethylglucose- cytosine.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In mammalian DNA, variant bases with methyl groups or phosphosulfate may be found.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Depending on the sequencing technique, a particular modification, e.g., the 5mC (5-Methylcytosine) common in humans, may or may not be detected.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In almost all organisms, DNA is synthesized in vivo using only the 4 canonical bases; modification that occurs post replication creates other bases like 5 methyl C.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] However, some bacteriophage can incorporate a non standard base directly.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In addition to modifications, DNA is under constant assault by environmental agents such as UV and Oxygen radicals.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] At the present time, the presence of such damaged bases is not detected by most DNA sequencing methods, although PacBio has published on this.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA) was first discovered and isolated by Friedrich Miescher in 1869, but it remained under-studied for many decades because proteins, rather than DNA, were thought to hold the genetic blueprint to life.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This situation changed after 1944 as a result of some experiments by Oswald Avery, Colin MacLeod, and Maclyn McCarty demonstrating that purified DNA could change one strain of bacteria into another.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This was the first time that DNA was shown capable of transforming the properties of cells.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In 1953, James Watson and Francis Crick put forward their double-helix model of DNA, based on crystallized X-ray structures being studied by Rosalind Franklin.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] According to the model, DNA is composed of two strands of nucleotides coiled around each other, linked together by hydrogen bonds and running in opposite directions.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Each strand is composed of four complementary nucleotides – adenine (A), cytosine (C), guanine (G) and thymine (T) – with an A on one strand always paired with T on the other, and C always paired with G.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] They proposed that such a structure allowed each strand to be used to reconstruct the other, an idea central to the passing on of hereditary information between generations.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The foundation for sequencing proteins was first laid by the work of Frederick Sanger who by 1955 had completed the sequence of all the amino acids in insulin, a small protein secreted by the pancreas.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This provided the first conclusive evidence that proteins were chemical entities with a specific molecular pattern rather than a random mixture of material suspended in fluid.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Sanger's success in sequencing insulin spurred on x-ray crystallographers, including Watson and Crick, who by now were trying to understand how DNA directed the formation of proteins within a cell.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Soon after attending a series of lectures given by Frederick Sanger in October 1954, Crick began developing a theory which argued that the arrangement of nucleotides in DNA determined the sequence of amino acids in proteins, which in turn helped determine the function of a protein.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] RNA sequencing was one of the earliest forms of nucleotide sequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The major landmark of RNA sequencing is the sequence of the first complete gene and the complete genome of Bacteriophage MS2, identified and published by Walter Fiers and his coworkers at the University of Ghent (Ghent, Belgium), in 1972 and 1976.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Traditional RNA sequencing methods require the creation of a cDNA molecule which must be sequenced.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The first method for determining DNA sequences involved a location-specific primer extension strategy established by Ray Wu, a geneticist, at Cornell University in 1970.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA polymerase catalysis and specific nucleotide labeling, both of which figure prominently in current sequencing schemes, were used to sequence the cohesive ends of lambda phage DNA.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Between 1970 and 1973, Wu, scientist Radha Padmanabhan and colleagues demonstrated that this method can be employed to determine any DNA sequence using synthetic location-specific primers.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Walter Gilbert, a biochemist, and Allan Maxam, a molecular geneticist, at Harvard also developed sequencing methods, including one for "DNA sequencing by chemical degradation".
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In 1973, Gilbert and Maxam reported the sequence of 24 basepairs using a method known as wandering-spot analysis.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Advancements in sequencing were aided by the concurrent development of recombinant DNA technology, allowing DNA samples to be isolated from sources other than viruses.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Two years later in 1975, Frederick Sanger, a biochemist, and Alan Coulson, a genome scientist, developed a method to sequence DNA.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The technique known as the "Plus and Minus" method, involved supplying all the components of the DNA but excluding the reaction of one of the four bases needed to complete the DNA.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In 1976, Gilbert and Maxam, invented a method for rapidly sequencing DNA while at Harvard, known as the Maxam–Gilbert sequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The technique involved treating radiolabelled DNA with a chemical and using a polyacrylamide gel to determine the sequence.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In 1977, Sanger then adopted a primer-extension strategy to develop more rapid DNA sequencing methods at the MRC Centre, Cambridge, UK.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This technique was similar to his "Plus and Minus" strategy, however, it was based upon the selective incorporation of chain-terminating dideoxynucleotides (ddNTPs) by DNA polymerase during in vitro DNA replication.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Sanger published this method in the same year.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The first full DNA genome to be sequenced was that of bacteriophage φX174 in 1977.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Medical Research Council scientists deciphered the complete DNA sequence of the Epstein-Barr virus in 1984, finding it contained 172,282 nucleotides.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Completion of the sequence marked a significant turning point in DNA sequencing because it was achieved with no prior genetic profile knowledge of the virus.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] A non-radioactive method for transferring the DNA molecules of sequencing reaction mixtures onto an immobilizing matrix during electrophoresis was developed by Herbert Pohl and co-workers in the early 1980s.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Followed by the commercialization of the DNA sequencer "Direct-Blotting-Electrophoresis-System GATC 1500" by GATC Biotech, which was intensively used in the framework of the EU genome-sequencing programme, the complete DNA sequence of the yeast *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* chromosome II.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Hood's laboratory at the California Institute of Technology announced the first semi-automated DNA sequencing machine in 1986.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This was followed by Applied Biosystems' marketing of the first fully automated sequencing machine, the ABI 370, in 1987 and by Dupont's Genesis 2000 which used a novel fluorescent labeling technique enabling all four dideoxynucleotides to be identified in a single lane.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] National Institutes of Health (NIH) had begun large-scale sequencing trials on *Mycoplasma capricolum*, *Escherichia coli*, *Caenorhabditis elegans*, and *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* at a cost of US$0.75 per base.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Meanwhile, sequencing of human cDNA sequences called expressed sequence tags began in Craig Venter's lab, an attempt to capture the coding fraction of the human genome.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In 1995, Venter, Hamilton Smith, and colleagues at The Institute for Genomic Research (TIGR) published the first complete genome of a free-living organism, the bacterium *Haemophilus influenzae*.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The circular chromosome contains 1,830,137 bases and its publication in the journal Science marked the first published use of whole-genome shotgun sequencing, eliminating the need for initial mapping efforts.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] By 2003, the Human Genome Project's shotgun sequencing methods had been used to produce a draft sequence of the human genome; it had a 92% accuracy.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In 2022, scientists successfully sequenced the last 8% of the human genome.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The fully sequenced standard reference gene is called GRCh38.p14, and it contains 3.1 billion base pairs.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Several new methods for DNA sequencing were developed in the mid to late 1990s and were implemented in commercial DNA sequencers by 2000.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Together these were called the "next-generation" or "second-generation" sequencing (NGS) methods, in order to distinguish them from the earlier methods, including Sanger sequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In contrast to the first generation of sequencing, NGS technology is typically characterized by being highly scalable, allowing the entire genome to be sequenced at once.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Usually, this is accomplished by fragmenting the genome into small pieces, randomly sampling for a fragment, and sequencing it using one of a variety of technologies, such as those described below.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] An entire genome is possible because multiple fragments are sequenced at once (giving it the name "massively parallel" sequencing) in an automated process.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] NGS technology has tremendously empowered researchers to look for insights into health, anthropologists to investigate human origins, and is catalyzing the "Personalized Medicine" movement.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] However, it has also opened the door to more room for error.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] There are many software tools to carry out the computational analysis of NGS data, often compiled at online platforms such as CSI NGS Portal, each with its own algorithm.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Even the parameters within one software package can change the outcome of the analysis.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In addition, the large quantities of data produced by DNA sequencing have also required development of new methods and programs for sequence analysis.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Several efforts to develop standards in the NGS field have been attempted to address these challenges, most of which have been small-scale efforts arising from individual labs.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Most recently, a large, organized, FDA-funded effort has culminated in the BioCompute standard.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] On 26 October 1990, Roger Tsien, Pepi Ross, Margaret Fahnestock and Allan J Johnston filed a patent describing stepwise ("base-by-base") sequencing with removable 3' blockers on DNA arrays (blots and single DNA molecules).
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In 1996, Pål Nyrén and his student Mostafa Ronaghi at the Royal Institute of Technology in Stockholm published their method of pyrosequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] On 1 April 1997, Pascal Mayer and Laurent Farinelli submitted patents describing DNA colony sequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The DNA sample preparation and random surface-polymerase chain reaction (PCR) arraying methods described in this patent, coupled to Roger Tsien et al.'s "base-by-base" sequencing method, is now implemented in Illumina's Hi-Seq genome sequencers.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In 1998, Phil Green and Brent Ewing of the University of Washington described their phred quality score for sequencer data analysis, a landmark analysis technique that gained widespread adoption, and which is still the most common metric for assessing the accuracy of a sequencing platform.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Lynx Therapeutics published and marketed massively parallel signature sequencing (MPSS), in 2000.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This method incorporated a parallelized, adapter/ligation-mediated, bead-based sequencing technology and served as the first commercially available "next-generation" sequencing method, though no DNA sequencers were sold to independent laboratories.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Allan Maxam and Walter Gilbert published a DNA sequencing method in 1977 based on chemical modification of DNA and subsequent cleavage at specific bases.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Also known as chemical sequencing, this method allowed purified samples of double-stranded DNA to be used without further cloning.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This method's use of radioactive labeling and its technical complexity discouraged extensive use after refinements in the Sanger methods had been made.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Maxam-Gilbert sequencing requires radioactive labeling at one 5' end of the DNA and purification of the DNA fragment to be sequenced.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Chemical treatment then generates breaks at a small proportion of one or two of the four nucleotide bases in each of four reactions (G, A+G, C, C+T).
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The concentration of the modifying chemicals is controlled to introduce on average one modification per DNA molecule.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Thus a series of labeled fragments is generated, from the radiolabeled end to the first "cut" site in each molecule.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The fragments in the four reactions are electrophoresed side by side in denaturing acrylamide gels for size separation.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] To visualize the fragments, the gel is exposed to X-ray film for autoradiography, yielding a series of dark bands each corresponding to a radiolabeled DNA fragment, from which the sequence may be inferred.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This method is mostly obsolete as of 2023.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The chain-termination method developed by Frederick Sanger and coworkers in 1977 soon became the method of choice, owing to its relative ease and reliability.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] When invented, the chain-terminator method used fewer toxic chemicals and lower amounts of radioactivity than the Maxam and Gilbert method.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Because of its comparative ease, the Sanger method was soon automated and was the method used in the first generation of DNA sequencers.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Sanger sequencing is the method which prevailed from the 1980s until the mid-2000s.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Over that period, great advances were made in the technique, such as fluorescent labelling, capillary electrophoresis, and general automation.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] These developments allowed much more efficient sequencing, leading to lower costs.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The Sanger method, in mass production form, is the technology which produced the first human genome in 2001, ushering in the age of genomics.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] However, later in the decade, radically different approaches reached the market, bringing the cost per genome down from $100 million in 2001 to $10,000 in 2011.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The objective for sequential sequencing by synthesis (SBS) is to determine the sequencing of a DNA sample by detecting the incorporation of a nucleotide by a DNA polymerase.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] An engineered polymerase is used to synthesize a copy of a single strand of DNA and the incorporation of each nucleotide is monitored.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The principle of real-time sequencing by synthesis was first described in 1993 with improvements published some years later.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This principle of real-time sequencing-by-synthesis has been used for almost all massive parallel sequencing instruments, including 454, PacBio, IonTorrent, Illumina and MGI.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] On February 2025, Roche announced development of a new, proprietary sequencing method relying on small molecules.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This method "encode[s] the sequence of a target nucleic acid molecule (DNA or RNA) into a measurable surrogate polymer called an Xpandomer", and combined amplification with later detected by a nanopore platform with a CMOS camera.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Large-scale sequencing often aims at sequencing very long DNA pieces, such as whole chromosomes, although large-scale sequencing can also be used to generate very large numbers of short sequences, such as found in phage display.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] For longer targets such as chromosomes, common approaches consist of cutting (with restriction enzymes) or shearing (with mechanical forces) large DNA fragments into shorter DNA fragments.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The fragmented DNA may then be cloned into a DNA vector and amplified in a bacterial host such as *Escherichia coli*.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Short DNA fragments purified from individual bacterial colonies are individually sequenced and assembled electronically into one long, contiguous sequence.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Studies have shown that adding a size selection step to collect DNA fragments of uniform size can improve sequencing efficiency and accuracy of the genome assembly.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In these studies, automated sizing has proven to be more reproducible and precise than manual gel sizing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The term "*de novo* sequencing" specifically refers to methods used to determine the sequence of DNA with no previously known sequence.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] *De novo* translates from Latin as "from the beginning".
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Gaps in the assembled sequence may be filled by primer walking.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The different strategies have different tradeoffs in speed and accuracy; shotgun methods are often used for sequencing large genomes, but its assembly is complex and difficult, particularly with sequence repeats often causing gaps in genome assembly.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Most sequencing approaches use an *in vitro* cloning step to amplify individual DNA molecules, because their molecular detection methods are not sensitive enough for single molecule sequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Emulsion PCR isolates individual DNA molecules along with primer-coated beads in aqueous droplets within an oil phase.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] A polymerase chain reaction (PCR) then coats each bead with clonal copies of the DNA molecule followed by immobilization for later sequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Emulsion PCR is used in the methods developed by Marguilis et al.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] (commercialized by 454 Life Sciences), Shendure and Porreca et al.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] (also known as "polony sequencing") and SOLiD sequencing, (developed by Agencourt, later Applied Biosystems, now Life Technologies).
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Emulsion PCR is also used in the GemCode and Chromium platforms developed by 10x Genomics.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Shotgun sequencing is a sequencing method designed for analysis of DNA sequences longer than 1000 base pairs, up to and including entire chromosomes.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This method requires the target DNA to be broken into random fragments.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] After sequencing individual fragments using the chain termination method, the sequences can be reassembled on the basis of their overlapping regions.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This method was heavily used in the Human Genome Project.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The high demand for low-cost sequencing has driven the development of high-throughput sequencing technologies that parallelize the sequencing process, producing thousands or millions of sequences concurrently.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] High-throughput sequencing technologies are intended to lower the cost of DNA sequencing beyond what is possible with standard dye-terminator methods.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In ultra-high-throughput sequencing as many as 500,000 sequencing-by-synthesis operations may be run in parallel.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Such technologies led to the ability to sequence an entire human genome in as little as one day.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] As of 2019, corporate leaders in the development of high-throughput sequencing products included Illumina, Qiagen and ThermoFisher Scientific.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] SMRT sequencing is based on the sequencing by synthesis approach.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The DNA is synthesized in zero-mode wave-guides (ZMWs) – small well-like containers with the capturing tools located at the bottom of the well.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The sequencing is performed with use of unmodified polymerase (attached to the ZMW bottom) and fluorescently labelled nucleotides flowing freely in the solution.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The wells are constructed in a way that only the fluorescence occurring by the bottom of the well is detected.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The fluorescent label is detached from the nucleotide upon its incorporation into the DNA strand, leaving an unmodified DNA strand.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] According to Pacific Biosciences (PacBio), the SMRT technology developer, this methodology allows detection of nucleotide modifications (such as cytosine methylation).
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This happens through the observation of polymerase kinetics.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This approach allows reads of 20,000 nucleotides or more, with average read lengths of 5 kilobases.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In 2015, Pacific Biosciences announced the launch of a new sequencing instrument called the Sequel System, with 1 million ZMWs compared to 150,000 ZMWs in the PacBio RS II instrument.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] SMRT sequencing is referred to as "third-generation" or "long-read" sequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The DNA passing through the nanopore changes its ion current.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This change is dependent on the shape, size and length of the DNA sequence.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Each type of the nucleotide blocks the ion flow through the pore for a different period of time.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The method does not require modified nucleotides and is performed in real time.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Nanopore sequencing is referred to as "third-generation" or "long-read" sequencing, along with SMRT sequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Early industrial research into this method was based on a technique called 'exonuclease sequencing', where the readout of electrical signals occurred as nucleotides passed by alpha(α)-hemolysin pores covalently bound with cyclodextrin.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] However the subsequent commercial method, 'strand sequencing', sequenced DNA bases in an intact strand.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Two main areas of nanopore sequencing in development are solid state nanopore sequencing, and protein based nanopore sequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Protein nanopore sequencing utilizes membrane protein complexes such as α-hemolysin, MspA (*Mycobacterium smegmatis* Porin A) or CssG, which show great promise given their ability to distinguish between individual and groups of nucleotides.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In contrast, solid-state nanopore sequencing utilizes synthetic materials such as silicon nitride and aluminum oxide and it is preferred for its superior mechanical ability and thermal and chemical stability.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The fabrication method is essential for this type of sequencing given that the nanopore array can contain hundreds of pores with diameters smaller than eight nanometers.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The pore contains a detection region capable of recognizing different bases, with each base generating various time specific signals corresponding to the sequence of bases as they cross the pore which are then evaluated.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Precise control over the DNA transport through the pore is crucial for success.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Various enzymes such as exonucleases and polymerases have been used to moderate this process by positioning them near the pore's entrance.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The first of the high-throughput sequencing technologies, massively parallel signature sequencing (or MPSS, also called next generation sequencing), was developed in the 1990s at Lynx Therapeutics, a company founded in 1992 by Sydney Brenner and Sam Eletr.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] MPSS was a bead-based method that used a complex approach of adapter ligation followed by adapter decoding, reading the sequence in increments of four nucleotides.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This method made it susceptible to sequence-specific bias or loss of specific sequences.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Because the technology was so complex, MPSS was only performed 'in-house' by Lynx Therapeutics and no DNA sequencing machines were sold to independent laboratories.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Lynx Therapeutics merged with Solexa (later acquired by Illumina) in 2004, leading to the development of sequencing-by-synthesis, a simpler approach acquired from Manteia Predictive Medicine, which rendered MPSS obsolete.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] However, the essential properties of the MPSS output were typical of later high-throughput data types, including hundreds of thousands of short DNA sequences.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In the case of MPSS, these were typically used for sequencing cDNA for measurements of gene expression levels.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The polony sequencing method, developed in the laboratory of George M.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Church at Harvard, was among the first high-throughput sequencing systems and was used to sequence a full *E. coli* genome in 2005.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] It combined an in vitro paired-tag library with emulsion PCR, an automated microscope, and ligation-based sequencing chemistry to sequence an *E. coli* genome at an accuracy of >99.9999% and a cost approximately 1/9 that of Sanger sequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The technology was licensed to Agencourt Biosciences, subsequently spun out into Agencourt Personal Genomics, and eventually incorporated into the Applied Biosystems SOLiD platform.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Applied Biosystems was later acquired by Life Technologies, now part of Thermo Fisher Scientific.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] A parallelized version of pyrosequencing was developed by 454 Life Sciences, which has since been acquired by Roche Diagnostics.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The method amplifies DNA inside water droplets in an oil solution (emulsion PCR), with each droplet containing a single DNA template attached to a single primer-coated bead that then forms a clonal colony.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The sequencing machine contains many picoliter-volume wells each containing a single bead and sequencing enzymes.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Pyrosequencing uses luciferase to generate light for detection of the individual nucleotides added to the nascent DNA, and the combined data are used to generate sequence reads.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This technology provides intermediate read length and price per base compared to Sanger sequencing on one end and Solexa and SOLiD on the other.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Solexa, now part of Illumina, was founded by Shankar Balasubramanian and David Klenerman in 1998, and developed a sequencing method based on reversible dye-terminators technology, and engineered polymerases.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The reversible terminated chemistry concept was invented by Bruno Canard and Simon Sarfati at the Pasteur Institute in Paris.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] It was developed internally at Solexa by those named on the relevant patents.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In 2004, Solexa acquired the company Manteia Predictive Medicine in order to gain a massively parallel sequencing technology invented in 1997 by Pascal Mayer and Laurent Farinelli.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] It is based on "DNA clusters" or "DNA colonies", which involves the clonal amplification of DNA on a surface.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The cluster technology was co-acquired with Lynx Therapeutics of California.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Solexa Ltd. later merged with Lynx to form Solexa Inc.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In this method, DNA molecules and primers are first attached on a slide or flow cell and amplified with polymerase so that local clonal DNA colonies, later coined "DNA clusters", are formed.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] To determine the sequence, four types of reversible terminator bases (RT-bases) are added and non-incorporated nucleotides are washed away.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] A camera takes images of the fluorescently labeled nucleotides.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Then the dye, along with the terminal 3' blocker, is chemically removed from the DNA, allowing for the next cycle to begin.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Unlike pyrosequencing, the DNA chains are extended one nucleotide at a time and image acquisition can be performed at a delayed moment, allowing for very large arrays of DNA colonies to be captured by sequential images taken from a single camera.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Decoupling the enzymatic reaction and the image capture allows for optimal throughput and theoretically unlimited sequencing capacity.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] 30x) per day per instrument (equipped with a single camera).
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This method is an upgraded modification to combinatorial probe anchor ligation technology (cPAL) described by Complete Genomics which has since become part of Chinese genomics company BGI in 2013.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The two companies have refined the technology to allow for longer read lengths, reaction time reductions and faster time to results.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In addition, data are now generated as contiguous full-length reads in the standard FASTQ file format and can be used as-is in most short-read-based bioinformatics analysis pipelines.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The two technologies that form the basis for this high-throughput sequencing technology are DNA nanoballs (DNB) and patterned arrays for nanoball attachment to a solid surface.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA nanoballs are simply formed by denaturing double stranded, adapter ligated libraries and ligating the forward strand only to a splint oligonucleotide to form a ssDNA circle.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Faithful copies of the circles containing the DNA insert are produced utilizing Rolling Circle Amplification that generates approximately 300–500 copies.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The long strand of ssDNA folds upon itself to produce a three-dimensional nanoball structure that is approximately 220 nm in diameter.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Making DNBs replaces the need to generate PCR copies of the library on the flow cell and as such can remove large proportions of duplicate reads, adapter-adapter ligations and PCR induced errors.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The patterned array of positively charged spots is fabricated through photolithography and etching techniques followed by chemical modification to generate a sequencing flow cell.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Each spot on the flow cell is approximately 250 nm in diameter, are separated by 700 nm (centre to centre) and allows easy attachment of a single negatively charged DNB to the flow cell and thus reducing under or over-clustering on the flow cell.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Sequencing is then performed by addition of an oligonucleotide probe that attaches in combination to specific sites within the DNB.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The probe acts as an anchor that then allows one of four single reversibly inactivated, labelled nucleotides to bind after flowing across the flow cell.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Unbound nucleotides are washed away before laser excitation of the attached labels then emit fluorescence and signal is captured by cameras that is converted to a digital output for base calling.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The attached base has its terminator and label chemically cleaved at completion of the cycle.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The cycle is repeated with another flow of free, labelled nucleotides across the flow cell to allow the next nucleotide to bind and have its signal captured.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This process is completed a number of times (usually 50 to 300 times) to determine the sequence of the inserted piece of DNA at a rate of approximately 40 million nucleotides per second as of 2018.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Applied Biosystems' (now a Life Technologies brand) SOLiD technology employs sequencing by ligation.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Here, a pool of all possible oligonucleotides of a fixed length are labeled according to the sequenced position.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Oligonucleotides are annealed and ligated; the preferential ligation by DNA ligase for matching sequences results in a signal informative of the nucleotide at that position.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Each base in the template is sequenced twice, and the resulting data are decoded according to the 2 base encoding scheme used in this method.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Before sequencing, the DNA is amplified by emulsion PCR.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The resulting beads, each containing single copies of the same DNA molecule, are deposited on a glass slide.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The result is sequences of quantities and lengths comparable to Illumina sequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This sequencing by ligation method has been reported to have some issue sequencing palindromic sequences.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] (now owned by Life Technologies) developed a system based on using standard sequencing chemistry, but with a novel, semiconductor-based detection system.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This method of sequencing is based on the detection of hydrogen ions that are released during the polymerisation of DNA, as opposed to the optical methods used in other sequencing systems.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] A microwell containing a template DNA strand to be sequenced is flooded with a single type of nucleotide.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] If the introduced nucleotide is complementary to the leading template nucleotide it is incorporated into the growing complementary strand.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This causes the release of a hydrogen ion that triggers a hypersensitive ion sensor, which indicates that a reaction has occurred.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] If homopolymer repeats are present in the template sequence, multiple nucleotides will be incorporated in a single cycle.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This leads to a corresponding number of released hydrogens and a proportionally higher electronic signal.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA nanoball sequencing is a type of high throughput sequencing technology used to determine the entire genomic sequence of an organism.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The company Complete Genomics uses this technology to sequence samples submitted by independent researchers.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The method uses rolling circle replication to amplify small fragments of genomic DNA into DNA nanoballs.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Unchained sequencing by ligation is then used to determine the nucleotide sequence.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This method of DNA sequencing allows large numbers of DNA nanoballs to be sequenced per run and at low reagent costs compared to other high-throughput sequencing platforms.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] However, only short sequences of DNA are determined from each DNA nanoball which makes mapping the short reads to a reference genome difficult.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Heliscope sequencing is a method of single-molecule sequencing developed by Helicos Biosciences.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] It uses DNA fragments with added poly-A tail adapters which are attached to the flow cell surface.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The next steps involve extension-based sequencing with cyclic washes of the flow cell with fluorescently labeled nucleotides (one nucleotide type at a time, as with the Sanger method).
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The reads are performed by the Heliscope sequencer.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] What made this technology especially novel was that it was the first of its class to sequence non-amplified DNA, thus preventing any read errors associated with amplification steps.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] In 2009 a human genome was sequenced using the Heliscope, however in 2012 the company went bankrupt.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] There are two main microfluidic systems that are used to sequence DNA; droplet based microfluidics and digital microfluidics.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Microfluidic devices solve many of the current limitations of current sequencing arrays.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Abate et al. studied the use of droplet-based microfluidic devices for DNA sequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] These devices have the ability to form and process picoliter sized droplets at the rate of thousands per second.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The devices were created from polydimethylsiloxane (PDMS) and used Forster resonance energy transfer, FRET assays to read the sequences of DNA encompassed in the droplets.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Each position on the array tested for a specific 15 base sequence.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Fair et al. used digital microfluidic devices to study DNA pyrosequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Significant advantages include the portability of the device, reagent volume, speed of analysis, mass manufacturing abilities, and high throughput.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This study provided a proof of concept showing that digital devices can be used for pyrosequencing; the study included using synthesis, which involves the extension of the enzymes and addition of labeled nucleotides.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] Boles et al. also studied pyrosequencing on digital microfluidic devices.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] They used an electro-wetting device to create, mix, and split droplets.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The sequencing uses a three-enzyme protocol and DNA templates anchored with magnetic beads.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The device was tested using two protocols and resulted in 100% accuracy based on raw pyrogram levels.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] The advantages of these digital microfluidic devices include size, cost, and achievable levels of functional integration.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] DNA sequencing research, using microfluidics, also has the ability to be applied to the sequencing of RNA, using similar droplet microfluidic techniques, such as the method, inDrops.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p01] This shows that many of these DNA sequencing techniques will be able to be applied further and be used to understand more about genomes and transcriptomes.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Third generation technologies aim to increase throughput and decrease the time to result and cost by eliminating the need for excessive reagents and harnessing the processivity of DNA polymerase.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Another approach uses measurements of the electrical tunnelling currents across single-strand DNA as it moves through a channel.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Depending on its electronic structure, each base affects the tunnelling current differently, allowing differentiation between different bases.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] The use of tunnelling currents has the potential to sequence orders of magnitude faster than ionic current methods and the sequencing of several DNA oligomers and micro-RNA has already been achieved.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] This method of sequencing utilizes binding characteristics of a library of short single stranded DNA molecules (oligonucleotides), also called DNA probes, to reconstruct a target DNA sequence.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Non-specific hybrids are removed by washing and the target DNA is eluted.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Hybrids are re-arranged such that the DNA sequence can be reconstructed.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] The benefit of this sequencing type is its ability to capture a large number of targets with a homogenous coverage.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] A large number of chemicals and starting DNA is usually required.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] However, with the advent of solution-based hybridization, much less equipment and chemicals are necessary.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Mass spectrometry may be used to determine DNA sequences.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization time-of-flight mass spectrometry, or MALDI-TOF MS, has specifically been investigated as an alternative method to gel electrophoresis for visualizing DNA fragments.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] With this method, DNA fragments generated by chain-termination sequencing reactions are compared by mass rather than by size.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] The mass of each nucleotide is different from the others and this difference is detectable by mass spectrometry.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Single-nucleotide mutations in a fragment can be more easily detected with MS than by gel electrophoresis alone.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] MALDI-TOF MS can more easily detect differences between RNA fragments, so researchers may indirectly sequence DNA with MS-based methods by converting it to RNA first.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] The higher resolution of DNA fragments permitted by MS-based methods is of special interest to researchers in forensic science, as they may wish to find single-nucleotide polymorphisms in human DNA samples to identify individuals.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] These samples may be highly degraded so forensic researchers often prefer mitochondrial DNA for its higher stability and applications for lineage studies.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] MS-based sequencing methods have been used to compare the sequences of human mitochondrial DNA from samples in a Federal Bureau of Investigation database and from bones found in mass graves of World War I soldiers.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Early chain-termination and TOF MS methods demonstrated read lengths of up to 100 base pairs.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Researchers have been unable to exceed this average read size; like chain-termination sequencing alone, MS-based DNA sequencing may not be suitable for large *de novo* sequencing projects.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Even so, a 2010 study did use the short sequence reads and mass spectroscopy to compare single-nucleotide polymorphisms in pathogenic *Streptococcus* strains.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] In microfluidic Sanger sequencing the entire thermocycling amplification of DNA fragments as well as their separation by electrophoresis is done on a single glass wafer (approximately 10 cm in diameter) thus reducing the reagent usage as well as cost.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] In some instances researchers have shown that they can increase the throughput of conventional sequencing through the use of microchips.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Research will still need to be done in order to make this use of technology effective.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] This approach directly visualizes the sequence of DNA molecules using electron microscopy.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] This method is based on use of RNA polymerase (RNAP), which is attached to a polystyrene bead.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] One end of DNA to be sequenced is attached to another bead, with both beads being placed in optical traps.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] RNAP motion during transcription brings the beads in closer and their relative distance changes, which can then be recorded at a single nucleotide resolution.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] The sequence is deduced based on the four readouts with lowered concentrations of each of the four nucleotide types, similarly to the Sanger method.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] A comparison is made between regions and sequence information is deduced by comparing the known sequence regions to the unknown sequence regions.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] A method has been developed to analyze full sets of protein interactions using a combination of 454 pyrosequencing and an *in vitro* virus mRNA display method.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Specifically, this method covalently links proteins of interest to the mRNAs encoding them, then detects the mRNA pieces using reverse transcription PCRs.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] The mRNA may then be amplified and sequenced.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] The combined method was titled IVV-HiTSeq and can be performed under cell-free conditions, though its results may not be representative of *in vivo* conditions.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] While there are many different ways to sequence DNA, only a few dominate the market.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] The success of any DNA sequencing protocol relies upon the DNA or RNA sample extraction and preparation from the biological material of interest.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] After DNA or RNA extraction, samples may require further preparation depending on the sequencing method.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] For Sanger sequencing, either cloning procedures or PCR are required prior to sequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] In the case of next-generation sequencing methods, library preparation is required before processing.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Assessing the quality and quantity of nucleic acids both after extraction and after library preparation identifies degraded, fragmented, and low-purity samples and yields high-quality sequencing data.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Each year the National Human Genome Research Institute, or NHGRI, promotes grants for new research and developments in genomics.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] 2010 grants and 2011 candidates include continuing work in microfluidic, polony and base-heavy sequencing methodologies.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] The sequencing technologies described here produce raw data that needs to be assembled into longer sequences such as complete genomes (sequence assembly).
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] There are many computational challenges to achieve this, such as the evaluation of the raw sequence data which is done by programs and algorithms such as Phred and Phrap.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Other challenges have to deal with repetitive sequences that often prevent complete genome assemblies because they occur in many places of the genome.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] As a consequence, many sequences may not be assigned to particular chromosomes.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] The production of raw sequence data is only the beginning of its detailed bioinformatical analysis.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Yet new methods for sequencing and correcting sequencing errors were developed.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Sometimes, the raw reads produced by the sequencer are correct and precise only in a fraction of their length.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Using the entire read may introduce artifacts in the downstream analyses like genome assembly, SNP calling, or gene expression estimation.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Two classes of trimming programs have been introduced, based on the window-based or the running-sum classes of algorithms.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Human genetics have been included within the field of bioethics since the early 1970s and the growth in the use of DNA sequencing (particularly high-throughput sequencing) has introduced a number of ethical issues.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] One key issue is the ownership of an individual's DNA and the data produced when that DNA is sequenced.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Regarding the DNA molecule itself, the leading legal case on this topic, *Moore v.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Regents of the University of California* (1990) ruled that individuals have no property rights to discarded cells or any profits made using these cells (for instance, as a patented cell line).
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] However, individuals have a right to informed consent regarding removal and use of cells.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Regarding the data produced through DNA sequencing, *Moore* gives the individual no rights to the information derived from their DNA.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] As DNA sequencing becomes more widespread, the storage, security and sharing of genomic data has also become more important.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] For instance, one concern is that insurers may use an individual's genomic data to modify their quote, depending on the perceived future health of the individual based on their DNA.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] In May 2008, the Genetic Information Nondiscrimination Act (GINA) was signed in the United States, prohibiting discrimination on the basis of genetic information with respect to health insurance and employment.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] As of 2013, eleven states have laws that can be interpreted to prohibit "DNA theft".
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Ethical issues have also been raised by the increasing use of genetic variation screening, both in newborns, and in adults by companies such as 23andMe.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] It has been asserted that screening for genetic variations can be harmful, increasing anxiety in individuals who have been found to have an increased risk of disease.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] For example, in one case noted in *Time*, doctors screening an ill baby for genetic variants chose not to inform the parents of an unrelated variant linked to dementia due to the harm it would cause to the parents.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] However, a 2011 study in *The New England Journal of Medicine* has shown that individuals undergoing disease risk profiling did not show increased levels of anxiety.
[src:genomics-computing/dna-sequencing-p02] Also, the development of Next Generation sequencing technologies such as Nanopore based sequencing has also raised further ethical concerns.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] In bioinformatics, **sequence assembly** refers to aligning and merging fragments from a longer DNA sequence in order to reconstruct the original sequence.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] This is needed as DNA sequencing technology might not be able to 'read' whole genomes in one go, but rather reads small pieces of between 20 and 30,000 bases, depending on the technology used.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Typically, the short fragments (reads) result from shotgun sequencing genomic DNA, or gene transcript (ESTs).
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] The problem of sequence assembly can be compared to taking many copies of a book, passing each of them through a shredder with a different cutter, and piecing the text of the book back together just by looking at the shredded pieces.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Besides the obvious difficulty of this task, there are some extra practical issues: the original may have many repeated paragraphs, and some shreds may be modified during shredding to have typos.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Excerpts from another book may also be added in, and some shreds may be completely unrecognizable.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Mapping/Aligning: assembling reads by aligning reads against a template (AKA reference).
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] The assembled consensus may not be identical to the template.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Reference-guided: grouping of reads by similarity to the most similar region within the reference (step wise mapping).
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Reads within each group are then shortened down to mimic short reads quality.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] A typical method to do so is the k-mer approach.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Reference-guided assembly is most useful using long-reads.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Referenced-guided assembly is a combination of the other types.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] This type is applied on long reads to mimic short reads advantages (i.e. call quality).
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] The logic behind it is to group the reads by smaller windows within the reference.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Reads in each group will then be reduced in size using the k-mer approach to select the highest quality and most probable contiguous sequence (contig).
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Contigs will then be joined together to create a scaffold.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] The final consensus is made by closing any gaps in the scaffold.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] The first sequence assemblers began to appear in the late 1980s and early 1990s as variants of simpler sequence alignment programs to piece together vast quantities of fragments generated by automated sequencing instruments called DNA sequencers.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Subsequent to these efforts, several other groups, mostly at the major genome sequencing centers, built large-scale assemblers, and an open source effort known as AMOS was launched to bring together all the innovations in genome assembly technology under the open source framework.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Expressed sequence tag or EST assembly was an early strategy, dating from the mid-1990s to the mid-2000s, to assemble individual genes rather than whole genomes.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] The problem differs from genome assembly in several ways.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] The input sequences for EST assembly are fragments of the transcribed mRNA of a cell and represent only a subset of the whole genome.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] A number of algorithmic problems differ between genome and EST assembly.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] For instance, genomes often have large amounts of repetitive sequences, concentrated in the intergenic regions.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Transcribed genes contain many fewer repeats, making assembly somewhat easier.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] On the other hand, some genes are expressed (transcribed) in very high numbers (e.g., housekeeping genes), which means that unlike whole-genome shotgun sequencing, the reads are not uniformly sampled across the genome.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] EST assembly is made much more complicated by features like (cis-) alternative splicing, trans-splicing, single-nucleotide polymorphism, and post-transcriptional modification.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Beginning in 2008 when RNA-Seq was invented, EST sequencing was replaced by this far more efficient technology, described under de novo transcriptome assembly.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] In terms of complexity and time requirements, de-novo assemblies are orders of magnitude slower and more memory intensive than mapping assemblies.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] This is mostly due to the fact that the assembly algorithm needs to compare every read with every other read (an operation that has a naive time complexity of O(*n*2)).
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Also, every shred would be compared with every other shred.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Handling repeats in de-novo assembly requires the construction of a graph representing neighboring repeats.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Such information can be derived from reading a long fragment covering the repeats in full or only its two ends.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] On the other hand, in a mapping assembly, parts with multiple or no matches are usually left for another assembling technique to look into.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] The complexity of sequence assembly is driven by two major factors: the number of fragments and their lengths.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] While more and longer fragments allow better identification of sequence overlaps, they also pose problems as the underlying algorithms show quadratic or even exponential complexity behaviour to both the number of fragments and their length.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] And while shorter sequences are faster to align, they also complicate the layout phase of an assembly as shorter reads are more difficult to use with repeats or near identical repeats.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] In the earliest days of DNA sequencing, scientists could only gain a few sequences of short length (some dozen bases) after weeks of work in laboratories.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Hence, these sequences could be aligned in a few minutes by hand.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] In 1975, the *dideoxy termination* method (AKA *Sanger sequencing*) was invented and until shortly after 2000, the technology was improved up to a point where fully automated machines could churn out sequences in a highly parallelised mode 24 hours a day.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] With the Sanger technology, bacterial projects with 20,000 to 200,000 reads could easily be assembled on one computer.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Larger projects, like the human genome with approximately 35 million reads, needed large computing farms and distributed computing.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] By 2004 / 2005, pyrosequencing had been brought to commercial viability by 454 Life Sciences.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] This new sequencing method generated reads much shorter than those of Sanger sequencing: initially about 100 bases, now 400–500 bases.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Its much higher throughput and lower cost (compared to Sanger sequencing) pushed the adoption of this technology by genome centers, which in turn pushed development of sequence assemblers that could efficiently handle the read sets.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] The sheer amount of data coupled with technology-specific error patterns in the reads delayed development of assemblers; at the beginning in 2004 only the Newbler assembler from 454 was available.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Released in mid-2007, the hybrid version of the MIRA assembler by Chevreux et al. was the first freely available assembler that could assemble 454 reads as well as mixtures of 454 reads and Sanger reads.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Assembling sequences from different sequencing technologies was subsequently coined *hybrid assembly*.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] From 2006, the Illumina (previously Solexa) technology has been available and can generate about 100 million reads per run on a single sequencing machine.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Compare this to the 35 million reads of the human genome project which needed several years to be produced on hundreds of sequencing machines.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Illumina was initially limited to a length of only 36 bases, making it less suitable for de novo assembly (such as de novo transcriptome assembly), but newer iterations of the technology achieved read lengths above 100 bases from both ends of a 3–400bp clone.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Announced at the end of 2007, the SHARCGS assembler by Dohm et al. was the first published assembler that was used for an assembly with Solexa reads.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] It was quickly followed by a number of others.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Later, new technologies like SOLiD from Applied Biosystems, Ion Torrent and SMRT were released and new technologies (e.g.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Nanopore sequencing) continued to emerge.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Despite the higher error rates of these technologies they are important for assembly because their longer read length helps to address the repeat problem.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] It is impossible to assemble through a perfect repeat that is longer than the maximum read length; however, as reads become longer the chance of a perfect repeat that large becomes small.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] This gives longer sequencing reads an advantage in assembling repeats even if they have low accuracy (≈85%).
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Most sequence assemblers have some algorithms built in for quality control, such as Phred.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] However, such measures do not assess assembly completeness in terms of gene content.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Some tools evaluate the quality of an assembly after the fact.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] For instance, BUSCO (Benchmarking Universal Single-Copy Orthologs) is a measure of gene completeness in a genome, gene set, or transcriptome, using the fact that many genes are present only as single-copy genes in most genomes.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] The initial BUSCO sets represented 3023 genes for vertebrates, 2675 for arthropods, 843 for metazoans, 1438 for fungi and 429 for eukaryotes.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Different organisms have a distinct region of higher complexity within their genome.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Hence, the need of different computational approaches is needed.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] is based on Graph theory in computer science.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] to assemble a contiguous sequence (contig) from reads.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] this approach scores each added read to the assembly and selects the highest possible score from the overlapping region.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Choose two fragments with the largest overlap.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Repeat steps 2 and 3 until only one fragment is left.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] The result might not be an optimal solution to the problem.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Filtering of reads: Reads that failed to pass the quality check should be removed from the FASTQ file to get the best assembly contigs.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Assembly: During this step, read alignment is utilized with different criteria to map each read to the possible location.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] The predicted position of a read is based on either how much of its sequence aligns with other reads or a reference.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Different alignment algorithms are used for reads from different sequencing technologies.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Some of the commonly used approaches in the assembly are de Bruijn graph and overlapping.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Read length, coverage, quality, and the sequencing technique used plays a major role in choosing the best alignment algorithm in the case of Next Generation Sequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] On the other hand, algorithms aligning 3rd generation sequencing reads requires advanced approaches to account for the high error rate associated with them.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Post-assembly: This step is focusing on extracting valuable information from the assembled sequence.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] Comparative genomics and population analysis are examples of post-assembly analysis.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] For a lists of *de-novo* assemblers, see De novo sequence assemblers.
[src:genomics-computing/genome-assembly] For a list of mapping aligners, see List of sequence alignment software § Short-read sequence alignment.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The field also includes studies of intragenomic (within the genome) phenomena such as epistasis (effect of one gene on another), pleiotropy (one gene affecting more than one trait), heterosis (hybrid vigour), and other interactions between loci and alleles within the genome.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] From the Greek ΓΕΝ *gen*, "gene" (gamma, epsilon, nu, epsilon) meaning "become, create, creation, birth", and subsequent variants: genealogy, genesis, genetics, genic, genomere, genotype, genus etc.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] While the word *genome* (from the German *Genom*, attributed to Hans Winkler) was in use in English as early as 1926, the term *genomics* was coined by Tom Roderick, a geneticist at the Jackson Laboratory (Bar Harbor, Maine), over beers with James E.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Womack, Tom Shows and Stephen O'Brien at a meeting held in Maryland on the mapping of the human genome in 1986.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] First as the name for a new journal and then as a whole new science discipline.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Following Rosalind Franklin's confirmation of the helical structure of DNA, James D.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Watson and Francis Crick's publication of the structure of DNA in 1953 and Fred Sanger's publication of the Amino acid sequence of insulin in 1955, nucleic acid sequencing became a major target of early molecular biologists.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Holley and colleagues published the first nucleic acid sequence ever determined, the ribonucleotide sequence of alanine transfer RNA.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Extending this work, Marshall Nirenberg and Philip Leder revealed the triplet nature of the genetic code and were able to determine the sequences of 54 out of 64 codons in their experiments.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] In 1972, Walter Fiers and his team at the Laboratory of Molecular Biology of the University of Ghent (Ghent, Belgium) were the first to determine the sequence of a gene: the gene for Bacteriophage MS2 coat protein.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Fiers' group expanded on their MS2 coat protein work, determining the complete nucleotide-sequence of bacteriophage MS2-RNA (whose genome encodes just four genes in 3569 base pairs [bp]) and Simian virus 40 in 1976 and 1978, respectively.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] shared half of the 1980 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for Independently developing methods for the sequencing of DNA.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] In addition to his seminal work on the amino acid sequence of insulin, Frederick Sanger and his colleagues played a key role in the development of DNA sequencing techniques that enabled the establishment of comprehensive genome sequencing projects.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] In 1975, he and Alan Coulson published a sequencing procedure using DNA polymerase with radiolabelled nucleotides that he called the *Plus and Minus technique*.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] This involved two closely related methods that generated short oligonucleotides with defined 3' termini.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] These could be fractionated by electrophoresis on a polyacrylamide gel (called polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis) and visualised using autoradiography.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The procedure could sequence up to 80 nucleotides in one go and was a big improvement, but was still very laborious.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Nevertheless, in 1977 his group was able to sequence most of the 5,386 nucleotides of the single-stranded bacteriophage φX174, completing the first fully sequenced DNA-based genome.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The refinement of the *Plus and Minus* method resulted in the chain-termination, or Sanger method (see below), which formed the basis of the techniques of DNA sequencing, genome mapping, data storage, and bioinformatic analysis most widely used in the following quarter-century of research.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] In the same year Walter Gilbert and Allan Maxam of Harvard University independently developed the Maxam-Gilbert method (also known as the *chemical method*) of DNA sequencing, involving the preferential cleavage of DNA at known bases, a less efficient method.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] For their groundbreaking work in the sequencing of nucleic acids, Gilbert and Sanger shared half the 1980 Nobel Prize in chemistry with Paul Berg (recombinant DNA).
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The advent of these technologies resulted in a rapid intensification in the scope and speed of completion of genome sequencing projects.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The first complete genome sequence of a eukaryotic organelle, the human mitochondrion (16,568 bp, about 16.6 kb [kilobase]), was reported in 1981, and the first chloroplast genomes followed in 1986.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] In 1992, the first eukaryotic chromosome, chromosome III of brewer's yeast *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* (315 kb) was sequenced.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The first free-living organism to be sequenced was that of *Haemophilus influenzae* (1.8 Mb [megabase]) in 1995.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The following year a consortium of researchers from laboratories across North America, Europe, and Japan announced the completion of the first complete genome sequence of a eukaryote, *S. cerevisiae* (12.1 Mb), and since then genomes have continued being sequenced at an exponentially growing pace.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] As of October 2011, the complete sequences are available for: 2,719 viruses, 1,115 archaea and bacteria, and 36 eukaryotes, of which about half are fungi.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Most of the microorganisms whose genomes have been completely sequenced are problematic pathogens, such as *Haemophilus influenzae*, which has resulted in a pronounced bias in their phylogenetic distribution compared to the breadth of microbial diversity.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Of the other sequenced species, most were chosen because they were well-studied model organisms or promised to become good models.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Yeast (*Saccharomyces cerevisiae*) has long been an important model organism for the eukaryotic cell, while the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster* has been a very important tool (notably in early pre-molecular genetics).
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The worm *Caenorhabditis elegans* is an often used simple model for multicellular organisms.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The zebrafish *Brachydanio rerio* is used for many developmental studies on the molecular level, and the plant *Arabidopsis thaliana* is a model organism for flowering plants.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The Japanese pufferfish (*Takifugu rubripes*) and the spotted green pufferfish (*Tetraodon nigroviridis*) are interesting because of their small and compact genomes, which contain very little noncoding DNA compared to most species.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The mammals dog (*Canis familiaris*), brown rat (*Rattus norvegicus*), mouse (*Mus musculus*), and chimpanzee (*Pan troglodytes*) are all important model animals in medical research.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] A rough draft of the human genome was completed by the Human Genome Project in early 2001, creating much fanfare.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] This project, completed in 2003, sequenced the entire genome for one specific person, and by 2007 this sequence was declared "finished" (less than one error in 20,000 bases and all chromosomes assembled).
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] In the years since then, the genomes of many other individuals have been sequenced, partly under the auspices of the 1000 Genomes Project, which announced the sequencing of 1,092 genomes in October 2012.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Completion of this project was made possible by the development of dramatically more efficient sequencing technologies and required the commitment of significant bioinformatics resources from a large international collaboration.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The continued analysis of human genomic data has profound political and social repercussions for human societies.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The English-language neologism **omics** informally refers to a field of study in biology ending in *-omics*, such as genomics, proteomics or metabolomics.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The related suffix **-ome** is used to address the objects of study of such fields, such as the genome, proteome, or metabolome (lipidome) respectively.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The suffix *-ome* as used in molecular biology refers to a *totality* of some sort; similarly **omics** has come to refer generally to the study of large, comprehensive biological data sets.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] While the growth in the use of the term has led some scientists (Jonathan Eisen, among others) to claim that it has been oversold, it reflects the change in orientation towards the quantitative analysis of complete or near-complete assortment of all the constituents of a system.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] In the study of symbioses, for example, researchers which were once limited to the study of a single gene product can now simultaneously compare the total complement of several types of biological molecules.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] After an organism has been selected, genome projects involve three components: the sequencing of DNA, the assembly of that sequence to create a representation of the original chromosome, and the annotation and analysis of that representation.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] As sequencing technology continues to improve, however, a new generation of effective fast turnaround benchtop sequencers has come within reach of the average academic laboratory.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] On the whole, genome sequencing approaches fall into two broad categories, *shotgun* and *high-throughput* (or *next-generation*) sequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] It is named by analogy with the rapidly expanding, quasi-random firing pattern of a shotgun.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Since gel electrophoresis sequencing can only be used for fairly short sequences (100 to 1000 base pairs), longer DNA sequences must be broken into random small segments which are then sequenced to obtain *reads*.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Multiple overlapping reads for the target DNA are obtained by performing several rounds of this fragmentation and sequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Computer programs then use the overlapping ends of different reads to assemble them into a continuous sequence.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Shotgun sequencing is a random sampling process, requiring over-sampling to ensure a given nucleotide is represented in the reconstructed sequence; the average number of reads by which a genome is over-sampled is referred to as coverage.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] For much of its history, the technology underlying shotgun sequencing was the classical chain-termination method or 'Sanger method', which is based on the selective incorporation of chain-terminating dideoxynucleotides by DNA polymerase during in vitro DNA replication.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Recently, shotgun sequencing has been supplanted by high-throughput sequencing methods, especially for large-scale, automated genome analyses.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] However, the Sanger method remains in wide use, primarily for smaller-scale projects and for obtaining especially long contiguous DNA sequence reads (>500 nucleotides).
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Chain-termination methods require a single-stranded DNA template, a DNA primer, a DNA polymerase, normal deoxynucleosidetriphosphates (dNTPs), and modified nucleotides (dideoxyNTPs) that terminate DNA strand elongation.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] These chain-terminating nucleotides lack a 3'-OH group required for the formation of a phosphodiester bond between two nucleotides, causing DNA polymerase to cease extension of DNA when a ddNTP is incorporated.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The ddNTPs may be radioactively or fluorescently labelled for detection in DNA sequencers.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Typically, these machines can sequence up to 96 DNA samples in a single batch (run) in up to 48 runs a day.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The high demand for low-cost sequencing has driven the development of high-throughput sequencing technologies that parallelize the sequencing process, producing thousands or millions of sequences at once.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] High-throughput sequencing is intended to lower the cost of DNA sequencing beyond what is possible with standard dye-terminator methods.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] In ultra-high-throughput sequencing, as many as 500,000 sequencing-by-synthesis operations may be run in parallel.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The Illumina dye sequencing method is based on reversible dye-terminators and was developed in 1996 at the Geneva Biomedical Research Institute, by Pascal Mayer and Laurent Farinelli.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] In this method, DNA molecules and primers are first attached on a slide and amplified with polymerase so that local clonal colonies, initially coined "DNA colonies", are formed.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Decoupling the enzymatic reaction and the image capture allows for optimal throughput and theoretically unlimited sequencing capacity; with an optimal configuration, the ultimate throughput of the instrument depends only on the A/D conversion rate of the camera.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The camera takes images of the fluorescently labeled nucleotides, then the dye along with the terminal 3' blocker is chemically removed from the DNA, allowing the next cycle.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] An alternative approach, ion semiconductor sequencing, is based on standard DNA replication chemistry.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] This technology measures the release of a hydrogen ion each time a base is incorporated.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] A microwell containing template DNA is flooded with a single nucleotide, if the nucleotide is complementary to the template strand it will be incorporated and a hydrogen ion will be released.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] This release triggers an ISFET ion sensor.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] If a homopolymer is present in the template sequence multiple nucleotides will be incorporated in a single flood cycle, and the detected electrical signal will be proportionally higher.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Overlapping reads form contigs; contigs and gaps of known length form scaffolds.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Paired end reads of next generation sequencing data mapped to a reference genome.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Multiple, fragmented sequence reads must be assembled together on the basis of their overlapping areas.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Sequence assembly refers to aligning and merging fragments of a much longer DNA sequence in order to reconstruct the original sequence.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] This is needed as current DNA sequencing technology cannot read whole genomes as a continuous sequence, but rather reads small pieces of between 20 and 1000 bases, depending on the technology used.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Third generation sequencing technologies such as PacBio or Oxford Nanopore routinely generate sequencing reads 10-100 kb in length; however, they have a high error rate at approximately 1 percent.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Typically the short fragments, called reads, result from shotgun sequencing genomic DNA, or gene transcripts (ESTs).
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Assembly can be broadly categorized into two approaches: *de novo* assembly, for genomes which are not similar to any sequenced in the past, and comparative assembly, which uses the existing sequence of a closely related organism as a reference during assembly.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Relative to comparative assembly, *de novo* assembly is computationally difficult (NP-hard), making it less favourable for short-read NGS technologies.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Within the *de novo* assembly paradigm there are two primary strategies for assembly, Eulerian path strategies, and overlap-layout-consensus (OLC) strategies.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] OLC strategies ultimately try to create a Hamiltonian path through an overlap graph which is an NP-hard problem.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Eulerian path strategies are computationally more tractable because they try to find a Eulerian path through a deBruijn graph.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Finished genomes are defined as having a single contiguous sequence with no ambiguities representing each replicon.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The DNA sequence assembly alone is of little value without additional analysis.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] 3. attaching biological information to these elements.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Automatic annotation tools try to perform these steps *in silico*, as opposed to manual annotation (a.k.a. curation) which involves human expertise and potential experimental verification.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Ideally, these approaches co-exist and complement each other in the same annotation pipeline (also see below).
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Traditionally, the basic level of annotation is using BLAST for finding similarities, and then annotating genomes based on homologues.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] More recently, additional information is added to the annotation platform.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The additional information allows manual annotators to deconvolute discrepancies between genes that are given the same annotation.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Some databases use genome context information, similarity scores, experimental data, and integrations of other resources to provide genome annotations through their Subsystems approach.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Ensembl) rely on both curated data sources as well as a range of software tools in their automated genome annotation pipeline.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] *Structural annotation* consists of the identification of genomic elements, primarily ORFs and their localisation, or gene structure.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] *Functional annotation* consists of attaching biological information to genomic elements.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The need for reproducibility and efficient management of the large amount of data associated with genome projects mean that computational pipelines have important applications in genomics.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Functional genomics is a field of molecular biology that attempts to make use of the vast wealth of data produced by genomic projects (such as genome sequencing projects) to describe gene (and protein) functions and interactions.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Functional genomics focuses on the dynamic aspects such as gene transcription, translation, and protein–protein interactions, as opposed to the static aspects of the genomic information such as DNA sequence or structures.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Functional genomics attempts to answer questions about the function of DNA at the levels of genes, RNA transcripts, and protein products.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] A key characteristic of functional genomics studies is their genome-wide approach to these questions, generally involving high-throughput methods rather than a more traditional "gene-by-gene" approach.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] A major branch of genomics is still concerned with sequencing the genomes of various organisms, but the knowledge of full genomes has created the possibility for the field of functional genomics, mainly concerned with patterns of gene expression during various conditions.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The most important tools here are microarrays and bioinformatics.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Structural genomics seeks to describe the 3-dimensional structure of every protein encoded by a given genome.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] This genome-based approach allows for a high-throughput method of structure determination by a combination of experimental and modeling approaches.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The principal difference between structural genomics and traditional structural prediction is that structural genomics attempts to determine the structure of every protein encoded by the genome, rather than focusing on one particular protein.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] As opposed to traditional structural biology, the determination of a protein structure through a structural genomics effort often (but not always) comes before anything is known regarding the protein function.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] This raises new challenges in structural bioinformatics, i.e. determining protein function from its 3D structure.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Epigenomics is the study of the complete set of epigenetic modifications on the genetic material of a cell, known as the epigenome.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Epigenetic modifications are reversible modifications on a cell's DNA or histones that affect gene expression without altering the DNA sequence (Russell 2010 p.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Two of the most characterized epigenetic modifications are DNA methylation and histone modification.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Epigenetic modifications play an important role in gene expression and regulation, and are involved in numerous cellular processes such as in differentiation/development and tumorigenesis.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The study of epigenetics on a global level has been made possible only recently through the adaptation of genomic high-throughput assays.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Metagenomics is the study of *metagenomes*, genetic material recovered directly from environmental samples.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The broad field may also be referred to as environmental genomics, ecogenomics or community genomics.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] While traditional microbiology and microbial genome sequencing rely upon cultivated clonal cultures, early environmental gene sequencing cloned specific genes (often the 16S rRNA gene) to produce a profile of diversity in a natural sample.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Such work revealed that the vast majority of microbial biodiversity had been missed by cultivation-based methods.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Recent studies use "shotgun" Sanger sequencing or massively parallel pyrosequencing to get largely unbiased samples of all genes from all the members of the sampled communities.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Because of its power to reveal the previously hidden diversity of microscopic life, metagenomics offers a powerful lens for viewing the microbial world that has the potential to revolutionize understanding of the entire living world.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Bacteriophages have played and continue to play a key role in bacterial genetics and molecular biology.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Historically, they were used to define gene structure and gene regulation.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Also the first genome to be sequenced was a bacteriophage.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] However, bacteriophage research did not lead the genomics revolution, which is clearly dominated by bacterial genomics.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Only very recently has the study of bacteriophage genomes become prominent, thereby enabling researchers to understand the mechanisms underlying phage evolution.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Bacteriophage genome sequences can be obtained through direct sequencing of isolated bacteriophages, but can also be derived as part of microbial genomes.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Analysis of bacterial genomes has shown that a substantial amount of microbial DNA consists of prophage sequences and prophage-like elements.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] A detailed database mining of these sequences offers insights into the role of prophages in shaping the bacterial genome: Overall, this method verified many known bacteriophage groups, making this a useful tool for predicting the relationships of prophages from bacterial genomes.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] At present there are 24 cyanobacteria for which a total genome sequence is available.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] 15 of these cyanobacteria come from the marine environment.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] These are six *Prochlorococcus* strains, seven marine *Synechococcus* strains, *Trichodesmium erythraeum* IMS101 and *Crocosphaera watsonii* WH8501.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Several studies have demonstrated how these sequences could be used very successfully to infer important ecological and physiological characteristics of marine cyanobacteria.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Thus, the growing body of genome information can also be tapped in a more general way to address global problems by applying a comparative approach.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Some new and exciting examples of progress in this field are the identification of genes for regulatory RNAs, insights into the evolutionary origin of photosynthesis, or estimation of the contribution of horizontal gene transfer to the genomes that have been analyzed.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Genomics has provided applications in many fields, including medicine, biotechnology, anthropology and other social sciences.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Next-generation genomic technologies allow clinicians and biomedical researchers to drastically increase the amount of genomic data collected on large study populations.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] When combined with new informatics approaches that integrate many kinds of data with genomic data in disease research, this allows researchers to better understand the genetic bases of drug response and disease.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Early efforts to apply the genome to medicine include those by a Medical College of Wisconsin team lead by Howard Jacob who developed the first tools for medical interpretation of both exome and whole human genomes in 2009.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] At the same time a Stanford team led by Euan Ashley was also developing tools for the medical interpretation of human genomes.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The Genomes2People research program at Brigham and Women's Hospital, Broad Institute and Harvard Medical School was established in 2012 to conduct empirical research in translating genomics into health.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Brigham and Women's Hospital opened a Preventive Genomics Clinic in August 2019, with Massachusetts General Hospital following a month later.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The *All of Us* research program aims to collect genome sequence data from 1 million participants to become a critical component of the precision medicine research platform and the *UK Biobank* initiative has studied more than 500.000 individuals with deep genomic and phenotypic data.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] The growth of genomic knowledge has enabled increasingly sophisticated applications of synthetic biology.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Craig Venter Institute announced the creation of a partially synthetic species of bacterium, *Mycoplasma laboratorium*, derived from the genome of *Mycoplasma genitalium*.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] Conservationists can use the information gathered by genomic sequencing in order to better evaluate genetic factors key to species conservation, such as the genetic diversity of a population or whether an individual is heterozygous for a recessive inherited genetic disorder.
[src:genomics-computing/genomics] By using genomic data to evaluate the effects of evolutionary processes and to detect patterns in variation throughout a given population, conservationists can formulate plans to aid a given species without as many variables left unknown as those unaddressed by standard genetic approaches.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] In genetics and bioinformatics, a **single-nucleotide polymorphism** (**SNP** /snɪp/; plural **SNPs** /snɪps/) is a germline substitution of a single nucleotide at a specific position in the genome.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Although certain definitions require the substitution to be present in a sufficiently large fraction of the population (e.g.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] 1% or more), many publications do not apply such a frequency threshold.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] For example, a G nucleotide present at a specific location in a reference genome may be replaced by an A in a minority of individuals.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The two possible nucleotide variations of this SNP – G or A – are called alleles.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs can help explain differences in susceptibility to a wide range of diseases across a population.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] For example, a common SNP in the CFH gene is associated with increased risk of age-related macular degeneration.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Differences in the severity of an illness or response to treatments may also be manifestations of genetic variations caused by SNPs.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] For example, two common SNPs in the *APOE* gene, rs429358 and rs7412, lead to three major APO-E alleles with different associated risks for development of Alzheimer's disease and age at onset of the disease.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Single nucleotide substitutions with an allele frequency of less than 1% are sometimes called single-nucleotide variants.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] "Variant" may also be used as a general term for any single nucleotide change in a DNA sequence, encompassing both common SNPs and rare mutations, whether germline or somatic.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The term single-nucleotide variant has therefore been used to refer to point mutations found in cancer cells.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] DNA variants must also commonly be taken into consideration in molecular diagnostics applications such as designing PCR primers to detect viruses, in which the viral RNA or DNA sample may contain single-nucleotide variants.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] However, this nomenclature uses arbitrary distinctions (such as an allele frequency of 1%) and is not used consistently across all fields; the resulting disagreement has prompted calls for a more consistent framework for naming differences in DNA sequences between two samples.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Single-nucleotide polymorphisms may fall within coding sequences of genes, non-coding regions of genes, or in the intergenic regions (regions between genes).
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs within a coding sequence do not necessarily change the amino acid sequence of the protein that is produced, due to degeneracy of the genetic code.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs in the coding region are of two types: synonymous SNPs and nonsynonymous SNPs.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Synonymous SNPs do not affect the protein sequence, while nonsynonymous SNPs change the amino acid sequence of protein.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs that are not in protein-coding regions may still affect gene splicing, transcription factor binding, messenger RNA degradation, or the sequence of noncoding RNA.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Gene expression affected by this type of SNP is referred to as an eSNP (expression SNP) and may be upstream or downstream from the gene.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] More than 600 million SNPs have been identified across the human genome in the world's population.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] A typical genome differs from the reference human genome at 4–5 million sites, most of which (more than 99.9%) consist of SNPs and short indels.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The genomic distribution of SNPs is not homogenous; SNPs occur in non-coding regions more frequently than in coding regions or, in general, where natural selection is acting and "fixing" the allele (eliminating other variants) of the SNP that constitutes the most favorable genetic adaptation.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Other factors, like genetic recombination and mutation rate, can also determine SNP density.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNP density can be predicted by the presence of microsatellites: AT microsatellites in particular are potent predictors of SNP density, with long (AT)(n) repeat tracts tending to be found in regions of significantly reduced SNP density and low GC content.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Since there are variations between human populations, a SNP allele that is common in one geographical or ethnic group may be rarer in another.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] However, this pattern of variation is relatively rare; in a global sample of 67.3 million SNPs, the Human Genome Diversity Project "found no such private variants that are fixed in a given continent or major region.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The highest frequencies are reached by a few tens of variants present at >70% (and a few thousands at >50%) in Africa, the Americas, and Oceania.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Within a population, SNPs can be assigned a minor allele frequency (MAF)—the lowest allele frequency at a locus that is observed in a particular population.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] This is simply the lesser of the two allele frequencies for single-nucleotide polymorphisms.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] With this knowledge, scientists have developed new methods in analyzing population structures in less studied species.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] By using pooling techniques, the cost of the analysis is significantly lowered.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] These techniques are based on sequencing a population in a pooled sample instead of sequencing every individual within the population by itself.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] With new bioinformatics tools, there is a possibility of investigating population structure, gene flow, and gene migration by observing the allele frequencies within the entire population.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] With these protocols there is a possibility for combining the advantages of SNPs with micro satellite markers.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] However, there is information lost in the process, such as linkage disequilibrium and zygosity information.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Single nucleotide polymorphisms serve as powerful molecular markers in contemporary genetic research and clinical practice.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Association studies, particularly genome-wide association studies (GWAS), represent the primary application of SNP technology for identifying genetic variants linked to human diseases and traits.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The development of tag SNP methodology has significantly enhanced the efficiency of genomic studies by exploiting patterns of linkage disequilibrium across the human genome.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Tag SNPs function as representative markers that capture genetic variation within specific chromosomal regions, allowing researchers to survey large genomic areas without genotyping every individual variant.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] This approach reduces both the financial cost and computational burden of large-scale genetic studies while maintaining sufficient power to detect disease-associated loci.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The selection of optimal tag SNPs relies on sophisticated algorithms that identify markers capable of capturing the maximum amount of genetic information within defined genomic intervals.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Haplotype reconstruction represents another fundamental application where SNPs enable the characterization of inherited genetic blocks.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Researchers utilize dense SNP maps to identify and analyze haplotype structures, which consist of sets of closely linked alleles that tend to be transmitted together through generations.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] These haplotype patterns provide insights into population history, demographic events, and evolutionary processes that have shaped contemporary genetic diversity.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The International HapMap Project exemplified this application by creating comprehensive maps of common haplotype patterns across diverse human populations.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Linkage disequilibrium analysis forms the theoretical foundation for many SNP-based applications in population genetics and disease mapping.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] This phenomenon describes the non-random association of alleles at different genomic positions, which occurs when variants are inherited together more frequently than would be expected by chance alone.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The extent of linkage disequilibrium between SNPs depends primarily on physical distance along chromosomes and local recombination rates, with closer variants generally showing stronger associations.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Understanding these patterns enables researchers to predict which SNPs will provide redundant information and guides the selection of informative markers for association studies.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] In genetic epidemiology, SNPs have emerged as essential tools for investigating disease transmission patterns and population structure.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Whole-genome sequencing approaches utilize SNP variation to define transmission clusters in infectious disease outbreaks, where cases showing similar genetic profiles may represent linked transmission events.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] This application has proven particularly valuable for tuberculosis surveillance and contact tracing, where traditional epidemiological methods may fail to identify all transmission links.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Additionally, SNP-based analyses contribute to understanding population stratification and ancestry, which are crucial factors in designing appropriate study controls and interpreting association results across diverse ethnic groups.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Variations in the DNA sequences of humans can affect how humans develop diseases and respond to pathogens, chemicals, drugs, vaccines, and other agents.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs are also critical for personalized medicine.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Examples include biomedical research, forensics, pharmacogenetics, and disease causation, as outlined below.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] One of the main contributions of SNPs in clinical research is genome-wide association study (GWAS).
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Genome-wide genetic data can be generated by multiple technologies, including SNP array and whole genome sequencing.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] GWAS has been commonly used in identifying SNPs associated with diseases or clinical phenotypes or traits.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Since GWAS is a genome-wide assessment, a large sample site is required to obtain sufficient statistical power to detect all possible associations.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Some SNPs have relatively small effect on diseases or clinical phenotypes or traits.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] To estimate study power, the genetic model for disease needs to be considered, such as dominant, recessive, or additive effects.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Due to genetic heterogeneity, GWAS analysis must be adjusted for race.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Candidate gene association study is commonly used in genetic study before the invention of high throughput genotyping or sequencing technologies.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Candidate gene association study is to investigate limited number of pre-specified SNPs for association with diseases or clinical phenotypes or traits.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] So this is a hypothesis driven approach.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Since only a limited number of SNPs are tested, a relatively small sample size is sufficient to detect the association.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Candidate gene association approach is also commonly used to confirm findings from GWAS in independent samples.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Genome-wide SNP data can be used for homozygosity mapping.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Homozygosity mapping is a method used to identify homozygous autosomal recessive loci, which can be a powerful tool to map genomic regions or genes that are involved in disease pathogenesis.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Recently, preliminary results reported SNPs as important components of the epigenetic program in organisms.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Moreover, cosmopolitan studies in European and South Asiatic populations have revealed the influence of SNPs in the methylation of specific CpG sites.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] In addition, meQTL enrichment analysis using GWAS database, demonstrated that those associations are important toward the prediction of biological traits.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs have historically been used to match a forensic DNA sample to a suspect but has been made obsolete due to advancing STR-based DNA fingerprinting techniques.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] However, the development of next-generation-sequencing (NGS) technology may allow for more opportunities for the use of SNPs in phenotypic clues such as ethnicity, hair color, and eye color with a good probability of a match.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] This can additionally be applied to increase the accuracy of facial reconstructions by providing information that may otherwise be unknown, and this information can be used to help identify suspects even without a STR DNA profile match.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Some cons to using SNPs versus STRs is that SNPs yield less information than STRs, and therefore more SNPs are needed for analysis before a profile of a suspect is able to be created.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Additionally, SNPs heavily rely on the presence of a database for comparative analysis of samples.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] However, in instances with degraded or small volume samples, SNP techniques are an excellent alternative to STR methods.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs (as opposed to STRs) have an abundance of potential markers, can be fully automated, and a possible reduction of required fragment length to less than 100 bp.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Pharmacogenetics focuses on identifying genetic variations including SNPs associated with differential responses to treatment.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Many drug metabolizing enzymes, drug targets, or target pathways can be influenced by SNPs.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The SNPs involved in drug metabolizing enzyme activities can change drug pharmacokinetics, while the SNPs involved in drug target or its pathway can change drug pharmacodynamics.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Therefore, SNPs are potential genetic markers that can be used to predict drug exposure or effectiveness of the treatment.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Genome-wide pharmacogenetic study is called pharmacogenomics.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Pharmacogenetics and pharmacogenomics are important in the development of precision medicine, especially for life-threatening diseases such as cancers.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Only small amount of SNPs in the human genome may have impact on human diseases.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Large scale GWAS has been done for the most important human diseases, including heart diseases, metabolic diseases, autoimmune diseases, and neurodegenerative and psychiatric disorders.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Most of the SNPs with relatively large effects on these diseases have been identified.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] These findings have significantly improved understanding of disease pathogenesis and molecular pathways, and facilitated development of better treatment.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Further GWAS with larger samples size will reveal the SNPs with relatively small effect on diseases.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] For common and complex diseases, such as type-2 diabetes, rheumatoid arthritis, and Alzheimer's disease, multiple genetic factors are involved in disease etiology.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] In addition, gene-gene interaction and gene-environment interaction also play an important role in disease initiation and progression.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] As there are for genes, bioinformatics databases exist for SNPs.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The International SNP Map working group mapped the sequence flanking each SNP by alignment to the genomic sequence of large-insert clones in Genebank.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] These alignments were converted to chromosomal coordinates that is shown in Table 1.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] This list has greatly increased since, with, for instance, the Kaviar database now listing 162 million single nucleotide variants.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The nomenclature for SNPs include several variations for an individual SNP, while lacking a common consensus.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The rs### standard is that which has been adopted by dbSNP and uses the prefix "rs", for "reference SNP", followed by a unique and arbitrary number.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs are frequently referred to by their dbSNP rs number, as in the examples above.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The Human Genome Variation Society (HGVS) uses a standard which conveys more information about the SNP.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The first section is usually a chromosome or mRNA identifier, such as NC_000023.10 (DNA) or NM_004006.3 (mRNA).
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The type of change is denoted by a string.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs can be easily assayed due to only containing two possible alleles and three possible genotypes involving the two alleles: homozygous A, homozygous B and heterozygous AB, leading to many possible techniques for analysis.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Some include: DNA sequencing; capillary electrophoresis; mass spectrometry; single-strand conformation polymorphism (SSCP); single base extension; electrochemical analysis; denaturating HPLC and gel electrophoresis; restriction fragment length polymorphism; and hybridization analysis.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] An important group of SNPs are those that corresponds to missense mutations causing amino acid change on protein level.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Point mutation of particular residue can have different effect on protein function (from no effect to complete disruption its function).
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Usually, change in amino acids with similar size and physico-chemical properties (e.g. substitution from leucine to valine) has mild effect, and opposite.
[src:genomics-computing/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Similarly, if SNP disrupts secondary structure elements (e.g. substitution to proline in alpha helix region) such mutation usually may affect whole protein structure and function.
[src:genomics-computing/variant-call-format] The **Variant Call Format** or **VCF** is a standard text file format used in bioinformatics for storing gene sequence or DNA sequence variations.
[src:genomics-computing/variant-call-format] The format was developed in 2010 for the 1000 Genomes Project and has since been used by other large-scale genotyping and DNA sequencing projects.
[src:genomics-computing/variant-call-format] VCF is a common output format for variant calling programs due to its relative simplicity and scalability.
[src:genomics-computing/variant-call-format] Many tools have been developed for editing and manipulating VCF files, including VCFtools, which was released in conjunction with the VCF format in 2011, and BCFtools, which was included as part of SAMtools until being split into an independent package in 2014.
[src:genomics-computing/variant-call-format] The standard is currently in version 4.5, although the 1000 Genomes Project has developed its own specification for structural variations such as duplications, which are not easily accommodated into the existing schema.
[src:genomics-computing/variant-call-format] Additional file formats have been developed based on VCF, including **genomic VCF** (**gVCF**). gVCF is an extended format which includes additional information about "blocks" that match the reference and their qualities.
[src:genomics-computing/variant-call-format] The header begins the file and provides metadata describing the body of the file.
[src:genomics-computing/variant-call-format] Header lines are denoted as starting with #.
[src:genomics-computing/variant-call-format] Special keywords in the header are denoted with ##.
[src:genomics-computing/variant-call-format] Recommended keywords include fileformat, fileDate and reference.
[src:genomics-computing/variant-call-format] The header contains keywords that optionally semantically and syntactically describe the fields used in the body of the file, notably INFO, FILTER, and FORMAT (see below).
[src:genomics-computing/variant-call-format] In practice, VCF headers often contain substantial metadata added by upstream software, such as reference genome information, contig definitions, filter descriptions, sample declarations, provenance fields, and custom INFO or FORMAT tags.
[src:genomics-computing/variant-call-format] This metadata is important for validation and interpretation.
[src:genomics-computing/variant-call-format] The body of VCF follows the header, and is tab separated into 8 mandatory columns and an unlimited number of optional columns that may be used to record other information about the sample(s).
[src:genomics-computing/variant-call-format] When additional columns are used, the first optional column is used to describe the format of the data in the columns that follow.
[src:genomics-computing/variant-call-format] Any other info fields are defined in the .vcf header.
[src:genomics-computing/variant-call-format] Any other format fields are defined in the .vcf header.
[src:genomics-computing/variant-call-format] Binary VCF or BCF files are binary, BGZF compressed variation of VCF files.
[src:genomics-computing/variant-call-format] BCF files allow fast and efficient indexed queries through tools like Tabix once an index file has been created.
